desc.1342: 100 songs of 2007. It was the first year of digital downloads being fully integrated into the charts, leading to many songs not given physical releases to enter the chart on download sales alone. Female singers such as Rihanna, Beyonce, Amy Winehouse and Leona Lewis had huge hits.
desc.1343: 100 songs of 2006. Timbaland was the most successful producer of this year. Turning pop acts such as Nelly Furtado and Justin Timberlake into RnB.  Downloaded music also began to dominate the charts. "Crazy" by Gnarls Barkley became the 1st song to top the UK chart on the basis of downloads alone.
desc.1344: 100 songs of 2005. Prominent music genres included girlgroup pop (Pussycat Dolls, Sugababes and Girls Aloud),  as well as Rock, Indie Rock and RnB. Mariah Carey was hugely successful topping the US year end singles chart with We Belong Together. Rihanna debuted her debut single Pon De Replay.
desc.1345: 100 songs of 2004. RnB continued to be huge with acts like Usher having the two best selling singles of the year in the USA, Ciara with her debut single Goodies and Destiny's Child's last album Destiny Fulfilled. Pop was also huge speccially with acts such as Britney Spears and Natasha Bedingfield.
desc.1346: 100 songs of 2003. RnB at its best, acts like 50 Cent, R Kelly, Kelis and Sean Paul had hits. Beyonce and Justin Timberlake debuted their first solo albums. The 2003 MTV VMA managed to cement itself as one of the biggest moments in pop culture history with Madonna, Britney and Christina's kiss.
desc.1348: 100 songs of 2002. At the same time RnB was emerging as the new trend on music, pop began to fade. Reality shows continued to release new acts such as Will Young, whose debut singe was the biggest selling single of that decade in the UK and Girls Aloud was formed in the UK show Popstars the Rivals.
desc.1349: 100 songs of 2001. Pop music was still very strong, with acts such as Kylie Minogue releasing the iconic Can't Get You Out Of My Head and some hip hop acts also on the rise like Shaggy and Destiny's Child. Hear'Say, created through the TV show Popstars UK, released the smash single Pure & Simple.
desc.1350: 100 songs of 2000. The year saw how competitive the industry had become over the 1990s with numerous new releases out each week. 2000 was particularly successful for Britney Spears, Moby, Eminem, Travis, Santana and The Beatles.
desc.1351: 100 songs of 1999.  Shania Twain's Come On Over was this year's most sucessful album topping the charts globally and the highest selling single was Britney Spears first hit Baby One More Time. Two main craze began during the year: the summer latino craze and high demand for Europop and Eurodance.
desc.1352: 100 songs of 1998. A transitional year for music, when the hyped up sound of pure pop from the mid-1990s began to fade and popular artists began to experiment with different styles and new artists were brought onto the scene. Cher's Belive was the biggest selling single of the year.
desc.1356: 100 songs 2012: the top 3 singles on tye year-end charts both in the USA and in the UK were the same: Gotye, Carly Rae Jepsen and Fun. On the albums charts, while Adele still topped the American year-end chart with 21, Emeli Sandé topped the British one. Little Mix released their debut album.
desc.1357: 100 songs of 2011. Adele was by far the biggest name in 2011. She topped the year end chart both in the UK and in the USA. One Direction and Ed Sheeran released their debut singles. Lady Gaga and Nicki Minaj released memorable albums. Robbie Williams released an album with Take That after 16 years.
desc.1359: 100 songs of 2010. Adele released the hugely successful Rolling In The Deep. Kesha had the best selling single of the USA with Tik Tok, making her the first female in history to top the year end chart with a debut single. In the UK, Eminem's Love The Way You Lie was the biggest selling single.
desc.1360: 100 songs of 2009. Due to the increase in downloads over physical sales, singles now tend to enter the chart at a lower position, before climbing to the top a few weeks later. So some songs there were released on 2008 were huge just in 2009. Lady Gaga and Black Eyed Peas were global phenomena.
desc.1361: 100 songs of 2008. While in the UK the two biggest selling singles of the year were X Factor related, in the USA Flo Rida topped the year ending chart with Low. Lady Gaga reinvented pop with the globally successful album The Fame. Katy Perry, Leona and Duffy were also huge with their debut albums.
